Why compiler padding changes structure memory footprints:

```cpp
// Struct footprint: 12 bytes due to 3-byte compiler padding after boolean
struct FPaddedStruct {
    int32_t ID;      // 4 bytes
    bool bActive;    // 1 byte (+ 3 bytes padding for 4-byte boundary alignment)
    float Scale;     // 4 bytes
};

// Struct footprint: 8 bytes (rearranged to pack members tight)
struct FPackedStruct {
    int32_t ID;      // 4 bytes
    float Scale;     // 4 bytes
    bool bActive;    // 1 byte (+ 3 bytes padding at end if aligned on 4-byte boundary, total 12? No, if on 8-byte boundary)
};
```
